expected, therefore, that switching between the degenerate and gapped states of the Dirac band can lead to a notable change in the spin Hall conductivity, even if such a switchable Dirac point or a Dirac nodal line is buried behind trivial Fermi surfaces $[40,41]$

In Figs. 3(a,b), we compare the calculated spin Berry curvature $\Omega_{x y}^{z}$ in the $k_{z}=\frac{\pi}{c}$ plane at $E=E_{F}$ for $\vec{n} \|[001]$ and $\vec{n} \|[010]$. We find that while $\Omega_{x y}^{z}$ is small for $\vec{n} \|$ [001] in the whole $k_{z}=\frac{\pi}{c}$ plane (Fig. 3(a)), it exhibits a notable peak for $\vec{n} \|$ [010] (Fig. 3(b)). Such a sharp peak appears at different energies and is associated with the Dirac nodal line. As seen from Fig. 3 (c), at the points where the nodal line crosses an equi-energy plane the spin Berry curvature is strongly enhanced (as is indicated by the color contrast in Fig. 3(c)). Such a sizable change in the spin Berry curvature affects the spin Hall conductivity. As is evident from Fig. 3(d), within the energy\\
